      <div class="col-xl-6 col-lg-8">
        <h2 class="mb-3">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <img loading="lazy" src="/images/sewing_faq.jpg" class="img-fluid" alt="Volunteers cutting out vests, May 2022">
      </div>
      <div class="row mt-5">
        <div class="col-lg-6">
        <h4>How long have you been doing this?</h4>
        <p>Jen conceived the Turtle Shelter Project in 2015 to help prevent people experiencing homelessness from freezing to death. We officially incorporated on April 3, 2017—Jen's sobriety anniversary—and received our 501(c)(3) status in 2018.</p>
        <p>We began in September 2017 with 450 volunteer hours, producing 50 prototype vests for testing. As of November 2024, we have distributed over 5,500 vests. With growing resources and improved efficiency, we recently produced and distributed 980 vests in under a month.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row mt-5">
      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <h4>If you want to help homeless people stay warm, why not just organize a coat drive?</h4>
        <p>
          Our foam insulation layer, combined with moisture-wicking fabrics, provides better insulation than traditional winter clothing. Foam vests retain warmth even when wet, helping to maintain core body temperature. Learn more in
          <a href="/vests">Our Vests</a>.
        </p>
        
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row mt-5">
      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <h4>What does the turtle in your logo represent?</h4>
        <p>A turtle carries its shelter wherever it goes. Similarly, our insulated vests are portable “shelters” that allow individuals to carry their warmth with them.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row mt-5">
      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <h4>How and where are the vests distributed?</h4>
        <p>During the winter of 2017, vests were tested and distributed in Ogden, Utah, with support from The Episcopal Church of the Good Shepherd and Youth Futures staff. By 2018, distribution expanded to Salt Lake County. We’ve since scaled nationally, including opening a chapter in Portland, Oregon.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row mt-5">
      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <h4>Why don’t you use a professional sewing shop to make the vests?</h4>
        <p>Our mission has two goals: providing warm clothing for those in need and offering opportunities for everyone to serve. This commitment inspired our motto: Every Life Has Value; Every Person Can Serve.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row mt-5">
      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <h4>I want to help, but I don’t sew.</h4>
        <p>Our vests are designed for volunteers with no special sewing skills. Tasks like marking and cutting can be done by anyone, and final construction is handled by our expert staff. Completed vests are returned to the community or sent to areas of need.</p>
      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="row mt-5">
      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <h4>How much of my donation goes to overhead?</h4>
        <p>Our overhead is minimal since all staff are volunteers. Annual expenses, including business registration, website hosting, a P.O. box, and liability insurance, totaled about 25% of our budget in 2018. Donations can also be earmarked for specific purposes. Please reach out with additional questions.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
